The clinic inside the Vatican will be deep cleaned, while the emergency room will remain open. VATICAN CITY - The Vatican on Friday reported its first coronavirus case, saying it had suspended outpatient services at its health clinic after a patient tested positive for COVID-19. The clinic inside the tiny city state -- which has some 1,000 residents -- will be deep cleaned, while the emergency room will remain open, spokesman Matteo Bruni told AFP. The patient tested positive on Thursday. READ:Â Pope 'tests negative for coronavirus' as Vatican ups controls The clinic is used by priests, residents and employees -- including those now retired -- as well as their relatives. Bruni said the Vatican was getting in touch with all those who had passed through the clinic, as per protocol.